{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dfb81b4d-fe91-4bed-a3d7-2e8e455948e6","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. Override `CreateWindow()` and hook into the window's events, or subclass `Window`:\n\n**Option 1 — Events in `App.xaml.cs`:**\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = new Window(new AppShell());\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Custom `Window` subclass:**\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated() { /* OnStart */ }\n    protected override void OnStopped() { /* OnSleep */ }\n    protected override void OnResumed() { /* OnResume */ }\n}\n```\n\n**Mapping summary:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI Window |\n|---------------|------------------|\n| `OnStart()`   | `Created` / `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep()`   | `Stopped` / `OnStopped()` |\n| `OnResume()`  | `Resumed` / `OnResumed()` |\n\nThe key shift is that lifecycle now lives on `Window`, not `Application`, since MAUI supports multi-window scenarios.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6ff45647-d9cc-4dd7-9b79-ebcb24e182bb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or override methods on the `Window` class. The `Application` class no longer has those virtual methods. Instead, you work with the `Window` class and its lifecycle methods/events.\n \nThe mapping is straightforward: `OnStart` maps to `Window.Created`, `OnSleep` to `Window.Deactivated` or `Window.Stopped`, and `OnResume` to `Window.Activated` or `Window.Resumed`. In .NET MAUI, you override `CreateWindow()` in your `Application` class to return a `Window` instance, then hook into those window lifecycle events to handle the same scenarios you managed before.","outputTokens":777,"requestId":"482A:3A5014:54A95CE:5CD1306:69F3FB3E"},"id":"22185270-16f8-4039-8bde-62e0e03bf501","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:00:59.635Z","parentId":"8809812c-6caf-4699-9ac5-3c391c7b66b6"}
